05620nam a22009255i 9780823287970DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20202020nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232879707 a10.1515/97808232879702doi  a(DE-B1597)566204  a(OCoLC)1153995708  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPS325bD96 2021 7aLIT0140002bisacsh04a811.5092231 aDworkin, Craig, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDictionary Poetics :bToward a Radical Lexicography /cCraig Dworkin. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b8  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aVerbal Arts: Studies in Poetics00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Toward an Experimental Lexicography -- t1. Funk & Wagnalls Practical Standard Dictionary of the English Language and Louis Zukofsky’s Thanks to the Dictionary -- t2. Webster’s Collegiate and Louis Zukofsky’s “A” -- t3. The Oxford English Dictionary and George Oppen’s Discrete Series -- t4. Webster’s New Collegiate and the Poetry of Clark Coolidge and Bernadette Mayer -- t5. The Random House Dictionary of the English Language and the Poetry of Tina Darragh -- t6. Juba to Jive: A Dictionary of African- American Slang and Harryette Mullen’s Muse & Drudge -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe new ways of writing pioneered by the literary avant-garde invite new ways of reading commensurate with their modes of composition. Dictionary Poetics examines one of those modes: book-length poems, from Louis Zukofsky to Harryette Mullen, all structured by particular editions of specific dictionaries. By reading these poems in tandem with their source texts, Dworkin puts paid to the notion that even the most abstract and fragmentary avant-garde literature is nonsensical, meaningless, or impenetrable. When read from the right perspective, passages that at first appear to be discontinuous, irrational, or hopelessly cryptic suddenly appear logically consistent, rationally structured, and thematically coherent.Following a methodology of “critical description,” Dictionary Poetics maps the material surfaces of poems, tracing the networks of signifiers that undergird the more familiar representational schemes with which conventional readings have been traditionally concerned. In the process, this book demonstrates that new ways of reading can yield significant interpretive payoffs, open otherwise unavailable critical insights into the formal and semantic structures of a composition, and transform our understanding of literary texts at their most fundamental levels.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAmerican poetryy20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican poetryy21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aCreation (Literary, artistic, etc.). 0aEnglish languagexLexicography. 0aPoetics. 4aAmerican Studies. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Poetry.2bisacsh  aClark Coolidge.  aDictionaries.  aGeorge Oppen.  aHarryette Mullen.  aLanguage Poetry.  aLexicography.  aLouis Zukofsky.  aObjectivism.  aPoetics.  aTina Darragh.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Englishz978311070474708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020z9783110704532oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2